  "to": "oagp-strategist",

  "subject": "Sub-org case for /oagp-init: forward-reference for non-MVP enhancement; non-trivial governance implications worth surfacing now while design is fresh (sub-org Director authority scope, write-limits to subtree, merge gating, cross-subtree visibility, parent-org override); idea captured for future analysis cycle",

  "sent": "2026-05-24T22:00:00-04:00",
  "action_required": false,

  "body": "Forward-reference idea memo to this seat. Filed per Director direction 2026-05-24 during /oagp-init design discussion: 'Agreed, parameter, but I don't think that's MVP. Now, you should absolutely file that as an idea, but it has all kinds of implications (among others, that means that we now have a human down further in the org chart, what does that actually mean? Are they write-limited to only their subtree?'. The standalone-org case is /oagp-init MVP; the sub-org case is forward work because it introduces a hierarchy that the current OAGP model doesn't address: OAGP assumes one Director at the top with bounded-authority discipline applying uniformly. A sub-org introduces a SECOND Director (or sub-Director-equivalent) lower in the org chart, with non-trivial implications: (1) Authority topology -- does the sub-org Director have full authority within their subtree, or is parent-org Director the ultimate ratifier? (2) Override -- can parent-org Director override sub-org decisions? Under what circumstances? (3) Merge gating -- if the sub-org has its own repo, who ratifies merges? Sub-org Director alone, or parent-org Director countersigns? (4) Write-limits -- per Director's question: 'Are they write-limited to only their subtree?' Probably yes for most filesystem/repo operations, but cross-subtree coordination memos must be possible. (5) Cross-subtree visibility -- can sub-org A see sub-org B's institutional history? By default? With permission? (6) Sub-org creation chain -- can a sub-org create its own sub-sub-orgs, recursively? Or is the hierarchy capped at depth-1? (7) Strategist-seat topology -- do sub-orgs have their own strategist seats, or do they inherit from the parent-org strategist? (8) Cross-org coordination conventions -- the current convention (memos to/from peer strategists) assumes peers; sub-org relationships aren't peer-shaped. This is a substantial proposal-cycle, not a minor enhancement. Bigger question lurking: does OAGP want to be a hierarchical-governance pattern (sub-orgs allowed), or does it stay flat (each org standalone, with peer coordination)? Both shapes are coherent; flat is the empirical default (each -def-spec is a peer of oagp-org structurally even if oagp-org consumes their formats). The sub-org enhancement would be a substantial pattern-shape evolution; not blocked, but warrants careful design when taken up.",
  "body_ref": "2026-05-24-2200--oagp-strategist--oagp-strategist--sub-org-governance-implications-idea.body.md",

